==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Bibliography
<hw>Bib`li*og"ra*phy</hw>
<pr>(b⟦icr⟧b`l⟦icr⟧*⟦ocr⟧g"r⟦adot⟧*f⟦ycr⟧)</pr> <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Bibliographies</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[Gr. <grk>bibliografi`a</grk>: cf. F.
<ets>bibliographie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a history or
description of books and manuscripts, with notices of the different
editions, the times when they were printed, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a list of books or other printed works having some
common theme, such as topic, period, author, or publisher.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>a list of the published (and sometimes unpublished)
sources of information referred to in a scholarly discourse or other
text, or used as reference materials for its preparation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>the branch of library science dealing with the
history and classification of books and other published
materials.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Bibliolatrist</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Bibliolater</ent>⟦br⟧
